*Swedish: [[endera]]
{{bottom}}

===Adverb===
'''either'''

# (''after a negative'') as well
#:''I don't like him and I don't like her '''either'''.''

====Synonyms====
* [[too]]

====Translations====
{{top}}
*French: [[non plus]]
*Italian: [[neanche]], [[nemmeno]], [[neppure]]
{{mid}}
*Russian: [[также]] [[не#Russian|не]] (tákže ne)
*Spanish: [[tampoco]]
*Swedish: [[heller]]
{{bottom}}

===Conjunction===
'''either'''

# Introduces the first of two options, the second of which is introduced by "[[or]]".
#:'''''Either''' you eat your dinner or you go to your room.''

====Translations====
{{top}}
*French: [[ou]], [[soit]]
*Italian: [[o#Italian|o]], [[oppure]]
{{mid}}
*Russian: [[либо]]...[[либо]] (líbo...líbo)
*Swedish: [[antingen]]
{{bottom}}

===Usage note===
* When there are more than two alternatives, "[[any]]" is used instead.

